---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import NewsletterCTA from '../components/NewsletterCTA.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';

const mailto = `mailto:${SITE.editorEmail}?subject=${encodeURIComponent(
  'Pitch — The Foundations of Software Engineering'
)}`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Write for us"
  description="The Foundations of Software Engineering is open to contributors. Pitch an essay on the durable ideas under the code."
>
  <article>
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="post-hero">
        <span class="kicker post-kicker">Call for writers<span class="dot">·</span>open</span>
        <h1 class="post-title">Write for the foundations.</h1>
        <p class="post-dek">
          This isn't a one-person newsletter by design. If you have opinions about the
          craft underneath the code, let's publish it.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-rule"><span class="mark">§</span></div>

      <div class="post-body">
        <p>
          <strong>The Foundations of Software Engineering</strong> is about the ideas that don't
          churn — abstraction, correctness, the cost of change, taste, the long half-life of good
          engineering. The best of those ideas come from people in the middle of the work, not
          from a single voice. So the door is open.
        </p>

        <h2>What I'm looking for</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Facts and opinions, not a tutorial.</strong> A claim about how software is built,
            defended from first principles. "Here's how to set up X" isn't it; "here's why X is the
            wrong default and what it costs you" is.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>From experience, not theory.</strong> Written by someone who has shipped it and
            paid for the lesson — specific, opinionated, and backed by the scars to prove it.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Durable over topical.</strong> If it would read as well in five years as it
            does today, it belongs here. If it dies with this quarter's release notes, it doesn't.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Roughly 1,000–2,500 words.</strong> Long enough to make a real case, short
            enough to respect the reader. Code is welcome when it earns its place.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What I'm not looking for</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Framework walkthroughs, release recaps, or "X vs. Y in 2026" listicles.</li>
          <li>Thinly veiled marketing for a product, course, or consultancy.</li>
          <li>AI-spun filler. Write something only you could have written.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What you get</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>A real edit — I work the draft with you until the argument is as sharp as it can be.</li>
          <li>Your byline, your bio, and links back to wherever you want readers to go.</li>
          <li>The full audience: the essay ships to the newsletter and lives on the site for good.</li>
          <li>Right to your own words — published here under a share-alike license, yours to repost.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How to pitch</h2>
        <p>
          Send me two or three sentences on the idea — the claim you want to make and why you're
          the one to make it. A rough draft is welcome but not required; a sharp paragraph beats a
          mediocre manuscript. I read everything and reply to anything with a pulse.
        </p>

        <p style="text-align:center; margin: 40px 0 8px;">
          <a class="cta-bracket" href={mailto}>Pitch an essay</a>
        </p>
        <p style="text-align:center; color: var(--ink-3); font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 11px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.16em;">
          {SITE.editorEmail}
        </p>

        <div class="post-end">❧</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <NewsletterCTA />
</BaseLayout>
